{
  "State Newton's Third Law.": "",
  "The total energy of an isolated system always remains constant": "",
  "An object at rest remains at rest unless acted on by a net force": "",
  "For every action there is an equal and opposite reaction": "",
  "The net force on an object equals its mass times acceleration": "",
  "Newton's Third Law: For every action force, there is an equal and opposite reaction force. The answer is 'For every action there is an equal and opposite reaction'. The other options — 'An object at rest remains at rest unless acted on by a net force', 'The net force on an object equals its mass times acceleration', and 'The total energy of an isolated system always remains constant' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "Action-reaction pairs act on how many objects?": "",
  "Three objects": "",
  "Two different objects": "",
  "It depends on the situation": "",
  "The same object": "",
  "Action-reaction pairs act on different objects — they never cancel each other. Common Misconceptions Action-reaction pairs do NOT cancel because they act on different objects. The other options — 'The same object', 'Three objects', and 'It depends on the situation' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "Why don't action-reaction pairs cancel each other?": "",
  "Because of friction": "",
  "Because they act on different objects": "",
  "They do cancel": "",
  "Because one is always larger": "",
  "Common Misconceptions Action-reaction pairs do NOT cancel because they act on different objects. The other options — 'Because one is always larger', 'They do cancel', and 'Because of friction' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "If a truck hits a small car, which experiences the greater force?": "",
  "Both experience the same force": "",
  "The truck": "",
  "Neither — no force occurs": "",
  "The car": "",
  "Newton's Third Law: when two objects interact, they exert equal and opposite forces on each other. The truck and car experience the SAME force, but different accelerations (F = ma). The answer is 'Both experience the same force'. The other options — 'The truck', 'The car', and 'Neither — no force occurs' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "How does a rocket propel itself in space?": "",
  "It uses magnetic fields": "",
  "It pushes against the air": "",
  "It expels exhaust gases backward; the gases push the rocket forward": "",
  "Solar wind pushes it": "",
  "A rocket expels exhaust gases downward → the gases push the rocket upward. The other options — 'It pushes against the air', 'It uses magnetic fields', and 'Solar wind pushes it' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "Does Newton's Third Law have exceptions?": "",
  "Yes, not for gravity": "",
  "No — it always applies": "",
  "Yes, not at high speeds": "",
  "Yes, not in space": "",
  "Newton's Third Law always applies for any interaction between two objects. Whenever object A exerts a force on object B, object B exerts an equal and opposite force on object A — no exceptions in classical mechanics.": "",
  "You push a wall. What is the reaction force?": "",
  "Friction pushes you sideways": "",
  "The wall pushes back on you with equal and opposite force": "",
  "Nothing — walls cannot exert force": "",
  "Gravity pulls you down": "",
  "Newton's Third Law: when two objects interact, they exert equal and opposite forces on each other. When you push on the wall, the wall pushes back on you with equal magnitude in the opposite direction.": "",
  "When you walk, what pushes you forward?": "",
  "Your muscles push your body forward directly through the air": "",
  "The ground pushes you forward as a reaction to your foot pushing backward": "",
  "Gravity pulls you forward in the direction you want to travel": "",
  "Air pressure behind you gives you a push in the forward direction": "",
  "When you walk, your foot pushes backward on the ground. By Newton's Third Law, the ground pushes your foot forward with an equal and opposite force (friction). This forward friction force is what propels you ahead.": "",
  "Are action and reaction forces equal in magnitude?": "",
  "Yes — they are always equal in magnitude and opposite in direction": "",
  "No — the action force is always larger than the reaction force": "",
  "Only when both objects have the same mass and the same size": "",
  "Only when the objects are not moving relative to each other": "",
  "Newton's Third Law guarantees that action and reaction forces are always equal in magnitude and opposite in direction, regardless of the masses or velocities of the objects involved.": "",
  "If the Earth pulls you downward with gravity, what is the reaction force?": "",
  "The normal force from the ground pushing you upward right now": "",
  "You pull the Earth upward with the same gravitational force": "",
  "Air resistance that pushes against your body on all sides": "",
  "Friction from the ground that prevents you from falling inward": "",
  "The action-reaction pair for gravity: Earth pulls you down, and you pull Earth up with the same force. The normal force from the ground is a separate force — it is not the reaction to your weight. Action-reaction pairs involve the same type of force between two objects.": "",
  "What does the term 'action force' mean in Newton's Third Law?": "",
  "The initial force that one object exerts on another object": "",
  "The strongest force in any interaction between two surfaces": "",
  "A force that only exists when an object is actively moving": "",
  "A force that does not have a corresponding partner force": "",
  "The action force is the force that one object exerts on another. In Newton's Third Law, the labels 'action' and 'reaction' are interchangeable — neither is more important. Every force is part of an action-reaction pair.": "",
  "What does the term 'reaction force' refer to?": "",
  "A force that is always weaker than the original action force": "",
  "The equal and opposite force exerted back on the first object": "",
  "A force that only appears after a significant time delay": "",
  "A force that cancels out the action force on the same object": "",
  "The reaction force is the force exerted back on the first object by the second object. It is equal in magnitude and opposite in direction to the action force. Importantly, it acts on a different object, so it does not cancel the action force.": "",
  "What does the term 'interaction' mean in the context of forces?": "",
  "A mutual exchange of forces between two objects that affect each other": "",
  "The motion of a single object through space with no outside contact": "",
  "The measurement of an object's mass on a scale in a laboratory": "",
  "The energy transfer that occurs when an object changes temperature": "",
  "An interaction in physics refers to two objects exerting forces on each other. Every force arises from an interaction. Newton's Third Law tells us that these mutual forces are always equal in magnitude and opposite in direction.": "",
  "What does 'equal and opposite' mean in Newton's Third Law?": "",
  "Same magnitude but pointing in the reverse direction on the other object": "",
  "Different magnitudes that add together to produce zero net force": "",
  "Forces that are identical in both size and direction on one object": "",
  "Forces that alternate back and forth between two different objects": "",
  "Equal and opposite means the two forces have the same magnitude (strength) but act in exactly opposite directions. The action force on object B and the reaction force on object A are the same size but point in reverse directions.": "",
  "What is an 'action-reaction pair'?": "",
  "Two equal forces on the same object that keep it in equilibrium": "",
  "Two forces of equal magnitude and opposite direction acting on two different objects": "",
  "Two forces that occur at different times during a collision event": "",
  "Two unrelated forces that happen to have the same numerical value": "",
  "An action-reaction pair consists of two forces that arise from a single interaction between two objects. They are equal in magnitude, opposite in direction, and act on different objects. They always exist simultaneously.": "",
  "What does 'thrust' mean in the context of rocket propulsion?": "",
  "The reaction force that propels a rocket forward when exhaust is expelled backward": "",
  "The gravitational force that pulls a rocket toward the center of the Earth": "",
  "The air resistance that slows a rocket as it moves through the atmosphere": "",
  "The friction between a rocket's body and the launch pad at the base": "",
  "Thrust is the forward force on a rocket created by expelling exhaust gases backward at high speed. By Newton's Third Law, as the rocket pushes gases backward, the gases push the rocket forward with an equal force.": "",
  "What does the phrase 'forces always come in pairs' mean?": "",
  "You cannot have a single force without a corresponding partner force": "",
  "Forces always act in groups of exactly two on the same single object": "",
  "Every object always has exactly two forces acting on it at all times": "",
  "Two identical forces always push an object in the same direction": "",
  "Newton's Third Law tells us that forces always come in pairs. Whenever one object exerts a force on another, the second object exerts an equal and opposite force back. A single, isolated force cannot exist.": "",
  "What does 'normal force' mean as a reaction force?": "",
  "The perpendicular push a surface exerts on an object resting on it": "",
  "The sideways friction force that prevents an object from sliding": "",
  "The gravitational attraction between two massive objects in space": "",
  "The tension in a rope that keeps a hanging object from falling": "",
  "The normal force is the perpendicular contact force that a surface exerts on an object pressing against it. When you place a book on a table, the book pushes down on the table, and the table pushes up on the book with a normal force.": "",
  "What does 'simultaneously' mean when describing action-reaction forces?": "",
  "The reaction force occurs a short time after the action force begins": "",
  "Both forces exist at exactly the same time with no delay between them": "",
  "The forces take turns acting one after the other in quick sequence": "",
  "One force must end completely before the other force can begin acting": "",
  "Action and reaction forces occur simultaneously — there is no time delay. The moment object A pushes on object B, object B pushes back on object A at that exact same instant. Neither force comes first.": "",
  "What does the term 'propulsion' mean?": "",
  "The process of driving or pushing an object forward using a force": "",
  "The process of slowing down an object using friction or drag forces": "",
  "The measurement of how heavy an object is in a gravitational field": "",
  "The resistance that an object has to any change in its velocity": "",
  "Propulsion is the process of pushing or driving an object forward. Rockets, jets, and cars all use propulsion — they generate a forward force (thrust) by applying Newton's Third Law, pushing something backward to move forward.": "",
  "A student jumps off a small boat onto a dock. The boat moves backward as the student jumps forward. Which principle explains why the boat moved backward?": "",
  "Newton's First Law — the boat was at rest and wanted to stay at rest": "",
  "Newton's Third Law — the student pushed the boat backward while jumping forward": "",
  "Gravity pulled the boat backward when the student's weight was removed": "",
  "Water currents underneath the boat pushed it in the opposite direction": "",
  "When the student pushes forward against the boat to jump, the boat pushes the student forward (reaction). But the student also pushes the boat backward (action on the boat). By Newton's Third Law, the forces are equal and opposite, so the boat moves backward.": "",
  "A swimmer pushes against the wall of a pool to start moving. What is the reaction force in this situation?": "",
  "The water resistance that slows the swimmer's body down gradually": "",
  "Gravity pulling the swimmer downward toward the bottom of the pool": "",
  "The wall pushes the swimmer forward with an equal and opposite force": "",
  "Buoyancy lifting the swimmer upward toward the surface of the water": "",
  "The swimmer pushes backward on the wall. By Newton's Third Law, the wall pushes the swimmer forward with an equal and opposite force. This reaction force from the wall propels the swimmer through the water.": "",
  "In a lab, a student releases an inflated balloon without tying it. The air rushes out the back and the balloon flies forward. What explains the balloon's forward motion?": "",
  "The air inside the balloon pushes the balloon forward as it escapes": "",
  "The balloon pushes air backward, and the escaping air pushes the balloon forward": "",
  "Gravity pulls the balloon forward because it becomes lighter as air leaves": "",
  "Static electricity between the rubber and the surrounding air propels it": "",
  "This is Newton's Third Law in action — just like a rocket. The balloon pushes air out the back (action), and the expelled air pushes the balloon forward (reaction). The forces are equal and opposite, propelling the balloon.": "",
  "A student on roller skates pushes against a friend who is also on roller skates. Both students move apart. Why does the pushing student also move?": "",
  "The friend transfers energy back through the push using body heat": "",
  "Air between them gets compressed and pushes the first student backward": "",
  "The friend exerts an equal and opposite reaction force on the pushing student": "",
  "The ground tilts slightly under the wheels causing the backward roll": "",
  "When the first student pushes the friend forward, by Newton's Third Law the friend pushes the first student backward with an equal force. Since both are on roller skates (low friction), both move apart in opposite directions.": "",
  "A student drops a ball and it hits the ground. During the collision, the ball exerts a downward force on the ground. What does the ground do?": "",
